15 October 2012 — European Parliament
Welcoming address of

Sen. Prof. Mario Monti, Prime Minister of Italy

(Check against delivery)

Dear

President of the European Commission, José Manuel Barroso

Commissioner for the internal market, Michel Barnier

Chairman of the Internal Market Committee, Malcom Harbour

Ladies and Gentlemen,

I am very honoured and pleased to have the opportunity to take part in this Conference that marks
such an important moment for the Union, the launch of the Single Market week, on the 20th
anniversary of the Single Market. I apologise for not being able to be with you today in person. But
I do hope you can see and hear me well.

Let me first congratulate President Barroso and you all on the Nobel Peace Prize to the Union. This
prize is a testament to the role played by the EU as a factor of integration and reconciliation among
the European peoples, overcoming the legacies of two World Wars. The EU has been a driver of
modernisation and democratisation for the countries of Europe coming out of dictatorships and
authoritarian regimes. It offers a model to be emulated by other parts of the world engaged in
regional cooperation.

I believe that the Single Market constitutes a major part of this achievement. It is the very
foundation of the European project. Market integration is not just a condition for the good
functioning of the EU economy. Market integration means the elimination of barriers between
peoples, cultures, societies and the expansion of individual freedoms. I agree with (former
Commission) President Jacques Delors that it’s difficult to fall in love with the single market. But it
is nevertheless easy to appreciate all the wonderful concrete things it has delivered.

What I always liked in the Single Market is that it embodies what is best in the European Union. It
is a grand political and economic project, but it can be explained in very few words. The aim of the
Single Market is very simple: to establish an area without barriers, where goods, services capital
and people can move freely. It is a very technical, bureaucratic task, as it concerns barriers,
regulations and tariffs, but at the same time it is the most concrete example of the values on which
the EU is founded: non discrimination, openess, freedom of choice, rule of law.

It is a very ambitious long term project, but it cannot be delivered through grand declarations or
political announcements. It can only be achieved step by step, through a modest, patient and
committed effort by all. Integrating markets among advanced economies is not just a exercise in
negative integration, by abrogating National regulations.

It is an example of ordnungspolitik, setting out rules and regulations that allow economic actors to
operate and compete fairly and in an efficient way in a common space of action.

It is a project around which different political cultures and socio economic models can converge.
The Single Market was a common goal embraced by the founding fathers and countries, of course,
but also the Anglo Saxon economies, the Nordic countries, the New Member States and the
Southern Mediterranean countries.

In my report on a new Strategy for the Single Market, I stressed that a new compromise was needed
among different political and economic cultures if the Single Market project was to gather the
political momentum to progress further and avoid the risk of disintegration.

Since its launch in 1992, the Single Market has been an important part of my professional life. I had
a chance to see its different phases of development and address its challenges from the Commission,
first as Commissioner responsible for Internal Market and Taxation and then for Competition. I
