raw_images/69490-8063_page_504,"Strategy for the Single Market at the service of Europe’s economy and society. Today, I follow the
policy debate on the Single Market as a member of the European Council and I see how it
represents an important component of the EU response to the economic and financial crisis. I am
among those Heads of State and Government who advocates that the Union gives a higher level of
priority to the Single Market in its strategy for growth and jobs.

These experiences taught me that completing the Single Market is a work in progress. By its very
nature, the Single Market is an evolving concept. There are always missing links and parts to be
completed, as there are new areas which need legal regulation or policy support. I want to commend
President Barroso and Commissioner Barnier for their determined effort to put the Single Market
back at the centre of the EU polcicy agenda with the Single Market Act I and II. Making progress in
market integration, notably in the new areas such as digital economy or in more traditional but key
areas as Energy and services, is crucial to restore growth, and is the best way to facilitate the
absorption of macro economic imbalances in the euro area. The legislative proposals we need are
there. Progress in their adoptionby the EU legislators is however not fast enough. We have now to
focus on governance, implementation and enforcement.

Moreover, we must not become complacent feeling that the Single Market will always continue to
move forward with a minimum investment of political capital. We all have a responsibility to
ensure that the Single Market remains a living political project. And the best way to do that is to
accept the uncomfortable truth that the Single Market is subject to risks of roll back and even of
disintegration.

In my Report I stressed that the Single Market was more needed than ever at a time in which it was
less loved than ever. I identified the risks coming from the fact that its intellectual foundations were
being challenged by the crisis. If the Single Market was in crisis, the market economy was even
more in crisis.

I believe that today we cannot ignore a new and potentially more dangerous threat to the Single
Market coming from the crisis of the euro area. One of the reasons for the introduction of the single
currency was that monetary integration was needed to address macroeconomic implications of the
creation of a Single Market. The euro was a tool to consolidate the achievement of the Single
Market project.

Over the past months, we have seen that the economic and financial crisis has progressively become
a factor of fragmentation of the single market along National lines. Because of excessively high
spreads on the sovereign bonds of some Member States, companies which have the same structure
and creditworthiness can access credit at very different rates when they are located in different parts
of the Single Market. Because of fears of a destruction of the integrity of the single currency, banks
have stopped lending to each other in the interbanks market across borders. National regulators
have tried to ring-fence assets owned by foreign banks in the subsidiaries located in their national
territory to protect the interests of National depositors in case of default. Most recently, we have
witnessed a resurgence of traditional protectionist reflexes against workers coming from other
Member States or even against goods imported from other Member countries.

We can best address these risks if we recognise them openly. We need to move forward with greater
integration of financial markets, completing the Single rule book, creating a single supervisory
mechanisms complemented in time by harmonised rules on guarantee of bank deposits and the
resolution of banking crisis, backed by a central resolution authority. I welcome the realistic
proposals put forward by the Commission in this regard.

We need also to consolidate the decisions of the June European Council on the stabilisation of
sovereign debt markets and on the use of the ESM to recapitalise banks directly, as soon as the
Single Supervisory System is established and effective.

Solutions should be specific to the euro area problems they intend to address, but they should be
open to the participation of all the Member States who want to take part in them. Any solutions
should respect the integrity of the Single Market and the unity of the EU institutions.
