possible, a strategic and very systematic approach towards enforcing
integrity is required. There are many different experiences in countries about
how best to structure that approach. Good practices exist to inspire policies.

One of the critical areas of government activities is public procurement. The
share of public procurement in GDP is on average around 15%. Many times,
in countries, public procurement is considered as an administrative task.
However, there are countries that pursue procurement from a strategic
perspective and aim at making a contribution to productivity growth. It
means procurement to open up markets, make participation in tenders
accessible to small and medium sized companies, make it really transparent,
so that in a complete procurement cycle obstacles and weaknesses can be
largely eliminated. Italy has a very interesting system in place, especially
through its central purchasing agency. Fine-tuning and further improvement
is possible but the example has been taken up in many places around the
world by people aiming at a good, efficient and competitive procurement
system.

It is true, public administration is just one player in a reform process, an
important one in most countries, but certainly not the only one. The justice
system plays an important role, and, of course, the Parliament. A very well
informed and very active civil society must be also part of the governance
system for carrying out an overhaul of economy and society.

