If you talk about the weight of public administration or the State in OECD
economies you are talking roughly about 50% of GDP. There are differences
among the countries and some of them quite substantial, but overall, over the
last few years, there is actually remarkable stability, rather than change. It
remains a significant part of the economy and reforming this part means that
not only changes occur within the public administration, but it also impacts
on the other 50% of the economy, in particular with respect to productivity.
However, the discussion is not, or should not be about the size of the public
sector, but about the quality of the public sector, especially in terms of
making strategically the right decisions. It is very important that this
discussion is not focused on big and small - it’s about smart government.

One element of the quality lies in the workforce of the public sector. As far as
ageing of the people working in central government is concerned, the
situation in Italy is dramatic. More than 50% of the people are over 50. It’s a
challenge, there’s no doubt about it, and Italy stands out, but others are not so
far away, compared to Belgium and Sweden. However, at the same time,
there is the potential for a big shift. People who will be leaving the public
sector will also allow for reorganizing the public sector, making it strategic
where you want it to be, making the investment where you think you need
more and reduce the workforce where it is no longer necessary. In an ageing
society, the replacement shift between education on the one hand and health
on the other hand is perhaps not one-to-one, but is definitely relevant for the
choices to be made.

In Italy, a large share of human resources are at sub-national level. It is not
sufficient to have a clear idea of the reform agenda at the central level. When
it comes to implementation there has to be a coordinated approach across all
the levels of government. The OECD has analyzed this in the context of
regulatory reform. Progress has been made and there is clearly a change at
the central level. The challenge, however, remains that regulatory reform has
to be also carried forward at the next level, and the next level is where, very
often, investment occurs and where jobs are to be created. How reform
efforts are aligned between the central government and lower levels of
government is critical for their overall success.

Another way to increase efficiency and make it easier for business and
citizens is, of course, a greater use of E-government. The statistics clearly
indicate that Italy has space for improvement. Many initiatives were
launched in the recent past. Still, the take-up of these services as measured in
2010 suggests that there is room for improvement in comparison with the
countries of the OECD.

Very good examples exist, where countries have made it much easier for the
citizens, as for business, to be in contact and in exchange with government. ‘E’
not just making it easier, but ‘e’ very often requires changes in the way
governments work. Without changing the back office, just putting
superfluous procedures in an e-context is not a very useful approach.

