I am very pleased to talk about modernizing the public administration in the
context of today’s Conference on Structural Reforms in Italy. Whenever
governments embark on a reform program, it is necessary and useful not
only to define what you need to do, but also about how to reform and who
should do it in the sense of taking accountability for implementation.

During our discussions this morning, we have heard several references to
experiences of making reform happen, a subject that the OECD has dealt with
for quite a while, and where we have looked at examples across sectors and
in a range of countries which tried to carry out major important reforms of
public policies. Mostly, countries are ready to report about the successes of
reforms; when it comes to the failures or to some of the unachieved reform
programs, they are normally less forthcoming but they exist. One of the first
things that emerged in our research is that governments can do a lot but
certainly not all and typically there are many more actors and stakeholders
involved, such as the private sector, citizens, activists, experts etc. The more
you involve them, the more you mobilize them, they take ownership more
easily, and therefore there is a greater chance of reforms to be successful.
Another question is whether reforms are exclusively driven by the central
government and/or also by local governments. Institutions matter. Let me
put it this way: we all seem to know it, but then again it is also forgotten in
many cases.

The OECD’s recommendations for reform used to focus on “go structural”.
The range of challenges of today lead us to extend them to “go social”, “go
green”, and now “go institutional”. The last few years of the crisis have been
demonstrating how much institutions matter for the success of public
policies and how their lack or weaknesses contribute to failures or are

associated with costs for society.

It is not just about the policies to be initiated and implemented, it is also a
question of the trust that good institutions can generate, both for investors
and citizens; in fact trust among citizens, trust among business and trust
among governments and citizens and the private sector.

